issue(id="0012" status="review")
  title Support Rust toolchains across clean bootstrap and dirty runtime
  user-story
    as-a scrubs maintainer supporting Rust-shaped project workflows
    i-want Rust toolchains to fit the clean/dirty scrubs model without ad hoc home leaks
    so-that clean `mise` bootstrap can install Rust tooling while dirty Rust workflows still run inside the intended boundary
  premise.
    Scrubs currently treats `mise` as a kind of bridge between clean space and
    dirty space. That model already works reasonably well for tools that
    install as self-contained binaries, but a fresh `puggers` guest showed two
    Rust-specific failures that make the boundary story incomplete.

    First, `mise install` for a repo that declares both `rust` and a
    `cargo:`-installed tool failed in a fresh guest because clean-side bootstrap
    lacked a C toolchain. Re-running the same install from `nix shell
    nixpkgs#gcc --command mise install` succeeded, which suggests that clean
    `mise` bootstrap legitimately needs access to at least some native build
    support for Rust-adjacent tool installation.

    Second, that successful bootstrap did not make ordinary dirty Rust commands
    work. Clean `mise` resolves `cargo` and `rustc` to rustup-managed proxies
    under `~/.cargo/bin`, and dirtyspace currently replaces the real home with
    a synthetic one. The result is that `cargo test` in the dirty runtime fails
    before compilation because bubblewrap cannot exec `/home/<user>/.cargo/bin/cargo`.

    The likely long-term fit is not "bind the real clean home into dirtyspace."
    The likely fit is a scrubs-owned Rust bridge model: clean bootstrap may
    materialize Rust toolchain state into explicit scrubs-managed locations,
    dirtyspace may consume the minimum read-only runtime surface it needs from
    that state, and writable Cargo caches or registries may need a separate
    dirty-visible home of their own. Once cargo actually runs in dirtyspace, we
    should also expect a follow-on policy decision about native build helpers
    such as `cc`, because many Rust workflows will eventually need one.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has a documented Rust support model that explains the roles of clean `mise`, rustup-managed toolchains, Cargo state, and dirty runtime execution without relying on implicit access to the real clean home.
    criterion A fresh guest can bootstrap a representative Rust repo whose `mise.toml` includes `rust` plus at least one `cargo:`-installed tool, without requiring manual operator surgery beyond the intended scrubs path.
    criterion Dirty Rust commands such as `cargo test` can execute through the scrubs launcher without depending on `~/.cargo/bin` or other paths that disappear when dirtyspace swaps in a synthetic home.
    criterion The chosen design makes an explicit decision about where Rustup and Cargo homes live, which parts are clean-owned versus dirty-visible, and which portions are read-only versus writable.
    criterion The design does not solve Rust support by broadly projecting the real clean `~/.cargo` or `~/.rustup` trees into dirtyspace.
    criterion If dirty Rust workflows require native build helpers such as `cc`, `c++`, `ar`, or `pkg-config`, scrubs defines whether that capability belongs in a reusable dirty Rust support path, a per-project shim, or some other explicit mechanism rather than relying on ambient leakage.
    criterion At least one validation path demonstrates both sides of the model: clean bootstrap can install the Rust toolchain and representative Cargo-installed tooling, and dirty runtime can execute a representative Rust workflow without reaching unrelated clean-space state.
  review-items
    item(status="covered").
      Scrubs now relocates Rust bootstrap state into scrubs-owned `mise`
      paths rather than the generic clean-home defaults. Clean `mise`
      installs Rust with `RUSTUP_HOME` under
      `~/.local/share/mise/rustup-home` and bootstrap `CARGO_HOME` under
      `~/.local/share/mise/rust-cargo-home`, while dirtyspace receives the
      intended Rust environment through the launcher rather than inheriting
      `~/.cargo` or `~/.rustup`.
    item(status="covered").
      Dirty Rust execution now works through the ordinary scrubs command path.
      The launcher resolves Rust tools through the scrubs-owned Rust bridge,
      provides a writable dirty `CARGO_HOME` inside the fake home, and no
      longer depends on rustup proxies that disappear when bubblewrap swaps in
      a synthetic home.
    item(status="covered").
      Fresh-guest validation now covers both the generic and motivating cases.
      A tiny Rust repo with `rust` plus `cargo:knope` completed plain
      `mise install` followed by plain repo-shell `cargo test`, and the
      original `puggers` repro completed `gh repo clone puggers`, plain
      `mise install`, and plain `cargo test` successfully in a fresh guest.
    item(status="covered").
      Fresh `puggers` guests now cover a minimization pass for the clean-side
      bootstrap toolchain. `mise install` plus dirty `cargo test` still passed
      after trimming `clean-base` down from `gcc`, `binutils`, `gnumake`, and
      `pkg-config` to just `gcc`, which still provides clean-side `cc`, `gcc`,
      and `ld` on `PATH` without exposing `make` or `pkg-config` as ambient
      clean commands.
    item(status="covered").
      Fresh `puggers` guests now cover a minimization pass for the Rust dirty
      helper basket. An empty basket failed in dirty `cargo test` with
      `linker 'cc' not found`, while a `cc`-only basket restored full
      end-to-end success for plain `mise install` and plain `cargo test`.
      For the motivating repo, the justified dirty Rust helper surface is now
      `cc` rather than the earlier broader basket.
    item(status="open").
      Validate what writable Cargo state dirtyspace actually needs over time,
      including registry caches, git checkouts, and incremental artifacts, and
      confirm that the fake-home `CARGO_HOME` shape remains a good long-term
      fit.
    item(status="covered").
      An explicit dirty-Rust probe now exists on `redteam`. A throwaway Rust
      repo executed both `build.rs` and test-time probing under ordinary
      scrubs `cargo`, recorded its observations in
      `~/rust-boundary-probe/probe-results.txt`, and summarized them in
      `~/SCRUBS_RUST_BOUNDARY_NOTES.md`. The probe confirmed that dirty Rust
      execution did not inherit `GH_TOKEN` or `CODEX_HOME`, could not see
      `~/.codex`, `~/.ssh`, or the clean-auth surface, could read the
      intended Rust bridge paths under `~/.local/share/mise`, and could not
      write back into those read-only bridge paths.
